1.2 Triggering Validation with @Valid


1.3 @Valid vs @Validated- The Distinction That Matters
............................................
@Valid is part of the standard Java Bean Validation API (javax.validation). @Validated is
Spring's own extension. They both trigger validation but @Validated adds one capability:
validation groups


@Valid vs @Validated comparison
// @Valid- standard, works on method parameters in controllers
public ResponseEntity<?> create(@Valid @RequestBody UserRequestDTO dto) {}
// @Validated- Spring extension, supports validation groups
// Also required when you want to validate method parameters
// in a @Service class (not just @RequestBody in controllers)
@Validated
@Service
public class UserService {
 public void processUser(@NotNull @Valid UserRequestDTO dto) {
 // Validation runs here too, inside the service
 }
}
// Also used for group-based conditional validation:
public interface OnCreate {}
public interface OnUpdate {}
public class UserRequestDTO {
 @NotNull(groups = OnCreate.class)
 private String email; // required on create, optional on update
}
// Controller selects which group to validate
@PostMapping
public ResponseEntity<?> create(
 @Validated(OnCreate.class) @RequestBody UserRequestDTO dto) {}


 ✓ In interviews: @Valid is sufficient for controller-level validation. Use @Validated when
you need method-level validation inside service classes, or when you have different rules for
create vs update operations.


Annotation           Passes                        Fails
@NotNull            "hello" | "" | " "             null
@NotEmpty          "hello" | " "                   null | ""
@NotBlank          "hello"                         null | "" | " "
@Size(min=2,
max=50)            "hi" | "hello"                   "a" | 66-char string



empty string, and whitespace-only strings in one annotation. @NotNull on a String field passes
for blank inputs, which is rarely what you want.
@NotNull has a legitimate use on non-String types: Integer, Long, Boolean, enum fields. You
cannot put @NotBlank on an Integer. Use @NotNull there, combined with @Min or @Max if you
need range checks.
One place to NOT use them: on fields you expect to be optional. If a user's phone number is
genuinely optional in your system, do not put @NotBlank on it. Add @Size only if it is provided,
using @Size alone (which allows null) or a custom validator.


1.5 A Production-Quality Request DTO
............................................

Here is what a real request DTO looks like when validation is applied thoughtfully, not just
sprayed on every fiel

UserRequestDTO.java
public class UserRequestDTO {
 @NotBlank(message = "Name is required")
 @Size(min = 2, max = 50, message = "Name must be between 2 and 50 characters")
 private String name;
 @NotBlank(message = "Email is required")
 @Email(message = "Must be a valid email address")
 private String email;
 @NotBlank(message = "Password is required")
 @Size(min = 8, message = "Password must be at least 8 characters")
 private String password;
 @NotNull(message = "Age is required")
 @Min(value = 18, message = "Must be at least 18 years old")

@Max(value = 120, message = "Age value is not realistic")
 private Integer age;
 // Optional field- no @NotBlank, only size constraint if provided
 @Size(max = 15, message = "Phone number too long")
 private String phone;
 // getters and setters
}


1.6 Nested Object Validation
..................................

When a DTO contains another object as a field, constraints on the inner object are ignored
unless you explicitly annotate the field with @Valid. This is one of the most missed pieces of
validation in fresher code.
Nested validation with @Valid on the inner object
public class OrderRequestDTO {
 @NotBlank(message = "Product name is required")
 private String productName;
 @NotNull(message = "Shipping address is required")
 @Valid // <-- Without this, AddressDTO constraints are NOT checked
 private AddressDTO shippingAddress;
}
public class AddressDTO {
 @NotBlank(message = "Street is required")
 private String street;
 @NotBlank(message = "City is required")
 private String city;
 @Pattern(regexp = "^[0-9]{6}$", message = "Pincode must be 6 digits")
 private String pincode;
}


