2.2 @RestControllerAdvice vs @ControllerAdvice
.....................................

@ControllerAdvice is the base annotation. It intercepts exceptions globally, but it does not
assume anything about the response format. If you use it, you need to add @ResponseBody to
each handler method, or your methods will try to resolve a view instead of returning JSON.


@RestControllerAdvice combines @ControllerAdvice and @ResponseBody. Every handler
method automatically serialises its return value to JSON. That is what you want in a REST API.

@ControllerAdvice vs @RestControllerAdvice
// Old way- requires @ResponseBody on each method
@ControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
 @ExceptionHandler(UserNotFoundException.class)
 @ResponseBody // <-- must not forget this
 public ResponseEntity<?> handleNotFound(...) { ... }
}



/ Modern way- @ResponseBody is implicit on all methods
@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
 @ExceptionHandler(UserNotFoundException.class)
 public ResponseEntity<?> handleNotFound(...) { ... }
}

✓ Use @RestControllerAdvice. It is the correct choice for REST APIs. If an interviewer
asks why, say: it combines @ControllerAdvice and @ResponseBody, ensuring all exception
handler methods return JSON without needing additional annotations on each one




2.3 Designing a Consistent Error Response
.......................
.......................


Spring's default error response looks different from your success responses. In a production
system, clients should be able to parse errors the same way they parse successes. A consistent
structure is not optional. It is the contract.
Target error response structure
// The structure every error response follows
{
 "timestamp": "2024-06-15T10:32:44",
 "status": 400,
 "message": "Validation failed",
 "errors": {
 "email": "Must be a valid email address",
 "name": "Name is required"
 },
 "path": "/api/users"
}




